'''Bijapur District''', formerly known as Birjapur, is one of the 27<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-01/india/30578413_1_new-districts-bastar-chhattisgarh |work=The Times Of India |title=Chhattisgarh carves out nine more districts |date=2012-01-01 }}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Districts of Chhattisgarh|districts]] of the state of [[Chhattisgarh]] in central [[India]]. It is one of the two new districts created on May 11, 2007. As of 2011 it is the second least populous district of Chhattisgarh (out of [[Districts of Chhattisgarh|18]]), after [[Narayanpur district|Narayanpur]].<!-- Are there 18 or 27 districts? --> It is the second-least literate district in India, with a literacy rate of at 41.58%, according to the 2011 census. [[Alirajpur district|Madhya Pradesh]]<ref name="distcensus">{{cite web | url = http://www.census2011.co.in/census/district/502-bijapur.html | title = Bijapur District Census 2011 | accessdate = 2011-10-11 | year = 2011 | publisher = Census2011.co.in}}</ref>

The present collector of Bijapur is Shri K D Kunjam (IAS).<ref>http://bijapur.gov.in</ref>

==History==
Bijapur district was formerly part of the [[Dantewada district]]. It is currently a part of the [[Red Corridor]]<!-- This sentence needs explanation - what is the red corridor? -->.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://intellibriefs.blogspot.com/2009/12/naxal-menace-83-districts-under.html |title=83 districts under the Security Related Expenditure Scheme |publisher=IntelliBriefs |date= 2009-12-11 |accessdate=2011-09-17}}</ref>

==Geography==
The Bijapur district occupies the south western part of Chhattisgarh. The district borders on the [[Narayanpur district]] to the north and the Dantewada district to the east. To the southwest, it borders on [[Telangana]] state, to the west on [[Maharashtra]] state.
Chhattisgarh Highest Waterfall Nambi Jaldhara about 540 feet (earlier was Teerathgarh Waterfall in Dantevada about 300 feet) Founded Near Usur, 64 km away from Bijapur.

[[Indravati River]], a key geographical feature of the district, flows across the southern part of the district. The highest hill is Bailadila or the "Bullock's Hump". It is situated to the south of the [[Indravati River]] and tilts towards north-south.

This district occupies an area of 6555&nbsp;km². [[Bijapur, Chhattisgarh|Bijapur]] is the administrative headquarters.<ref>{{cite book|last=Srivastava|first=Dayawanti et al (ed.)|title=India 2010, A Reference Annual|year=2010|publisher=Publications Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of Indiaand|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-230-1617-7|page=1122|url=http://www.publicationsdivision.nic.in/others/india_2010.pdf|access-date=2011-01-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101229223802/http://publicationsdivision.nic.in/others/India_2010.pdf|archive-date=2010-12-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> In total, the district comprises 675 villages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.webindia123.com/news/ar_showdetails.asp?id=705120475&cat=&n_date=20070512|title=2 new districts formed in Chhattisgarh |date=April 20, 2010}}</ref>

